1
00:01:36,700 --> 00:01:39,200
Now this is more like it.

2
00:01:43,200 --> 00:01:46,210
Relatively safe, quiet.

3
00:01:46,210 --> 00:01:48,210
Quiet?
It's a ghost town.

4
00:01:48,710 --> 00:01:50,210
It's the off season.

5
00:01:50,210 --> 00:01:54,210
Look how peaceful this is.
You're going to be missing
this after Memorial Day

6
00:01:54,210 --> 00:01:56,720
when the place is
crawling with tourists.

7
00:01:56,720 --> 00:01:58,720
Maybe.

8
00:01:58,720 --> 00:02:00,720
I just hope
someone's hiring.

9
00:02:04,220 --> 00:02:07,730
Yeah. Start slowing up
'cause we should be
coming up to it.

10
00:02:07,730 --> 00:02:09,730
What's the address?

11
00:02:09,730 --> 00:02:12,230
Uh, it's the Viking Motel.

12
00:02:12,230 --> 00:02:14,230
We're living in a motel?

13
00:02:14,230 --> 00:02:18,240
Oh, yeah. They rent out
long term when there's
no tourists around.

14
00:02:18,240 --> 00:02:20,740
There it is.
There it is.

15
00:02:23,740 --> 00:02:27,250
At least we know what
we'll be paying in rent.

16
00:02:27,250 --> 00:02:28,250
So will everyone else.

17
00:02:31,250 --> 00:02:35,250
I hope it's
a safe neighborhood.

18
00:02:35,250 --> 00:02:36,760
You're kidding, right?

19
00:02:36,760 --> 00:02:38,760
You can never be
too careful.

20
00:02:54,770 --> 00:02:56,280
Yes?

21
00:02:56,280 --> 00:02:59,780
Hi, I'm Rick Holland.
This is Kathryn Bennett.

22
00:03:00,280 --> 00:03:03,780
I spoke to you last week
about the apartment.

23
00:03:03,780 --> 00:03:06,290
Now wait a minute.

24
00:03:06,290 --> 00:03:09,290
You called last week?

25
00:03:09,290 --> 00:03:13,290
Yes, I told you
we'd be arriving
today or yesterday,

26
00:03:13,790 --> 00:03:15,800
and you said a unit
would be available.

27
00:03:15,800 --> 00:03:18,800
You came here
yesterday or today?

28
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:20,300
Well, which was it?

29
00:03:20,300 --> 00:03:25,810
No. We called you
last week from New York
about an apartment.

30
00:03:25,810 --> 00:03:29,810
Oh, New York!
You're the couple
from New York City!

31
00:03:29,810 --> 00:03:32,310
That wasn't yesterday
that I talked to you.

32
00:03:32,310 --> 00:03:35,820
That was last week.

33
00:03:35,820 --> 00:03:37,820
- How was the drive up?
- Oh, great.

34
00:03:37,820 --> 00:03:39,820
I suppose you want
to see the unit.

35
00:04:14,850 --> 00:04:17,860
Oh, I thought the unit
was on the second floor.

36
00:04:17,860 --> 00:04:19,360
It is.

37
00:04:19,360 --> 00:04:23,360
Too many keys.
I tried to have
just the one master,

38
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:26,870
but these people
keep changing
the lock on me.

39
00:04:39,380 --> 00:04:40,380
What do you think?

40
00:04:40,380 --> 00:04:42,380
Well, it's fine.

41
00:04:42,380 --> 00:04:45,380
I just-- I thought
we were going to be
on the second floor.

42
00:04:45,380 --> 00:04:48,390
Well, this is the model unit.

43
00:04:48,390 --> 00:04:52,390
It's been empty
for quite a while, so I
just use it to show people.

44
00:04:52,390 --> 00:04:57,400
All the units are the same.

45
00:04:57,400 --> 00:05:00,400
The one you two
would be getting is
on the second floor.

46
00:05:00,400 --> 00:05:03,400
But I'm getting old,

47
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:07,910
and you can't expect me
to go traipsing up and down
the stairs all day long,

48
00:05:07,910 --> 00:05:09,910
showing apartments if
people aren't going
to take it.

49
00:05:09,910 --> 00:05:11,910
That's fine,
if they're all the same.

50
00:05:11,910 --> 00:05:13,910
It's a great deal, you know.

51
00:05:13,910 --> 00:05:16,920
During the summer,
I can get $120 a night

52
00:05:16,920 --> 00:05:19,920
for a unit like this.

53
00:05:19,920 --> 00:05:25,930
But it's a been a little slow
the past few years,

54
00:05:25,930 --> 00:05:29,930
so we're all filled up
with long-termers.

55
00:05:29,930 --> 00:05:35,440
Now there's no guarantee
that you can stay past
the off season.

56
00:05:35,430 --> 00:05:37,440
We were pretty busy
last summer,

57
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:41,440
but we'll just have to see what
the tourist traffic is like.

58
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:44,440
Now, there's
no pets allowed...

59
00:05:44,440 --> 00:05:47,950
and no drugs.

60
00:05:47,950 --> 00:05:50,950
And you'll have
to sign a paper

61
00:05:50,950 --> 00:05:54,950
saying that you're not gonna
fool with the smoke detector.

62
00:06:14,470 --> 00:06:15,470
Hey.

63
00:06:17,980 --> 00:06:22,980
Well, we've actually
found someone who's
immune to your charms.

64
00:06:22,980 --> 00:06:23,980
I guess.

65
00:06:25,990 --> 00:06:29,490
- Oh, God.
- It smells in here.

66
00:06:30,990 --> 00:06:32,990
Probably just needs
airing out.

67
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:37,500
Finally, a bathroom.

68
00:06:41,500 --> 00:06:44,500
- Oh, my God. Oh, my God!
- What is it? Honey?

69
00:06:44,500 --> 00:06:46,510
- It's disgusting!
- What is it?

70
00:06:46,510 --> 00:06:49,010
Turn on the light!
Don't come in!

71
00:06:49,010 --> 00:06:51,010
- Oh! I'm gonna puke.
- Just get out of there.

72
00:06:51,010 --> 00:06:54,010
Wash yourself off
in the kitchen, I guess.

73
00:06:54,010 --> 00:06:57,520
- I can't believe this!
- I'm going to puke.

74
00:06:57,520 --> 00:06:59,520
- Excuse me. Excuse me! Hey!
- Yeah?

75
00:06:59,520 --> 00:07:02,520
We just moved into unit 16,
and the whole bathroom is
covered in excrement!

76
00:07:02,520 --> 00:07:04,520
- What?
- Excrement!
The lights were off

77
00:07:04,520 --> 00:07:07,030
and my girlfriend
went in there and
got it all over herself!

78
00:07:07,030 --> 00:07:09,530
- What are you talking about?
- Excrement!

79
00:07:09,530 --> 00:07:12,030
Feces! Poo-poo! Shit!

80
00:07:12,030 --> 00:07:13,530
It's everywhere in there!

81
00:07:13,530 --> 00:07:17,040
And you want me
to clean it up?

82
00:07:38,060 --> 00:07:41,560
Well, Mrs. Farthing
was beside herself,
apologizing.

83
00:07:41,560 --> 00:07:44,560
Are you gonna be
all right about living
on the first floor though?

84
00:07:44,560 --> 00:07:48,070
I just don't think
I could ever feel clean
in that bathroom after that.

85
00:07:48,070 --> 00:07:52,070
Me either. I can probably
rig something up
for these windows.

86
00:07:52,070 --> 00:07:55,070
If it makes you feel better,
but, honestly, I think
this town looks safer

87
00:07:55,070 --> 00:07:57,580
than where my dad lives
in Westchester.

88
00:07:57,580 --> 00:08:00,580
But there's a lot
of drifters and bikers
that go to towns like this.

89
00:08:00,580 --> 00:08:03,080
Stop worrying.
We'll be fine.

90
00:08:04,080 --> 00:08:07,090
Hey, you know,
the previous tenant in here
was a writer too.

91
00:08:07,090 --> 00:08:08,590
Really? What kind?

92
00:08:08,590 --> 00:08:12,590
Well, she didn't say,
but she did refer to him
as "Mr. Warren."

93
00:08:12,590 --> 00:08:15,590
Oh. You think it was
Peter Warren?

94
00:08:15,590 --> 00:08:18,100
Yeah, I think so.
He's from up here, you know.

95
00:08:18,100 --> 00:08:20,100
Maybe that'll give you
inspiration.

96
00:08:20,100 --> 00:08:23,100
To write a crappy best seller?
Let's hope not.

97
00:08:23,100 --> 00:08:25,610
- Still, it's pretty cool.
- [voice on radio]

98
00:08:25,600 --> 00:08:28,110
What is that noise?

99
00:08:28,110 --> 00:08:30,610
Mrs. Farthing said
the woman next door
has a police scanner,

100
00:08:30,610 --> 00:08:36,120
so we may need to move
the head of the bed to
the other side of the room.

101
00:08:36,120 --> 00:08:40,120
Um, in the meantime,
why don't you, uh,

102
00:08:40,120 --> 00:08:43,120
take those dirty hands off me
and get in the shower

103
00:08:43,120 --> 00:08:45,630
while I unload the car.

104
00:08:45,620 --> 00:08:47,630
Sounds like a plan.

105
00:09:11,650 --> 00:09:13,650
Warren!

106
00:09:13,650 --> 00:09:15,650
Hi.

107
00:09:16,160 --> 00:09:17,660
Are you all right?

108
00:09:17,660 --> 00:09:20,160
Oh. Yes.

109
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:24,660
Yes, of course.
New neighbor.

110
00:09:24,660 --> 00:09:25,660
Yeah, yeah.

111
00:09:25,660 --> 00:09:28,670
We're moving in
next door.

112
00:09:28,670 --> 00:09:30,170
I'm Rick.

113
00:09:30,170 --> 00:09:32,170
Of course you are.

114
00:09:33,670 --> 00:09:36,680
Oh, hey, moving in?
Want a plant?

115
00:09:36,680 --> 00:09:38,680
Excuse me?

116
00:09:38,680 --> 00:09:40,680
A houseplant.
A fern maybe?

117
00:09:41,680 --> 00:09:44,680
Never mind.

118
00:09:44,680 --> 00:09:47,690
Oh, hey, I guess
I should get to know
my new neighbor.

119
00:09:48,190 --> 00:09:49,190
The name's Ted.

120
00:09:49,190 --> 00:09:52,190
Hi, I'm Rick.
Rick Holland.

121
00:09:54,190 --> 00:09:55,700
Of course you are.

122
00:09:56,700 --> 00:10:00,200
[police scanner]

123
00:10:06,710 --> 00:10:08,210
[voice]
Kathryn?

124
00:10:12,710 --> 00:10:15,210
Kathryn. Beautiful name.

125
00:10:15,210 --> 00:10:17,720
So what brings Rick and Kathryn
from New York City

126
00:10:17,720 --> 00:10:19,720
up to our
horse's neck of the woods?

127
00:10:19,720 --> 00:10:22,220
Well,
I work in the theater,

128
00:10:22,220 --> 00:10:25,220
and New York is
pretty expensive.

129
00:10:25,220 --> 00:10:27,730
We moved up here
so I could finally
get some writing done

130
00:10:27,730 --> 00:10:30,230
and maybe open
one of my plays
in Portland.

131
00:10:30,230 --> 00:10:32,230
You know, kind of
an out-of-town tryout

132
00:10:32,230 --> 00:10:34,230
before bringing it
back to New York.

133
00:10:34,230 --> 00:10:36,740
The theater? I hear
these satellite TV people

134
00:10:36,740 --> 00:10:39,240
are putting you folks
out of business.

135
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:40,740
I think
we'll be okay.

136
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:42,740
Ah, you do.

137
00:10:45,740 --> 00:10:48,750
[police scanner]

138
00:10:54,750 --> 00:10:55,750
Rick?

139
00:10:57,760 --> 00:11:00,260
[police scanner]

140
00:11:03,260 --> 00:11:04,260
[thump]

141
00:11:04,760 --> 00:11:06,770
[scanner off]

142
00:11:13,270 --> 00:11:16,780
I thought that we'd be
getting a lot of snow
up here this time of year.

143
00:11:16,780 --> 00:11:18,780
Not snow.

144
00:11:18,780 --> 00:11:19,780
Rain.

145
00:11:19,780 --> 00:11:22,780
You see? Wet.

146
00:11:22,780 --> 00:11:26,790
Yeah, I saw that.
I guess I thought,
you know,

147
00:11:26,790 --> 00:11:28,790
this time of year
we'd be buried in snow.

148
00:11:28,790 --> 00:11:32,790
Snow, sleet, rain.
We get all sorts of
miserable weather here.

149
00:11:32,790 --> 00:11:35,290
The worst of the snow
generally piles up inland.

150
00:11:35,290 --> 00:11:37,800
Here on the coast,
it's usually rain this year.

151
00:11:37,800 --> 00:11:41,800
Gonna be a wet winter.
Forty days and forty nights.

152
00:11:43,300 --> 00:11:46,310
Well, I guess I'll--
I'll be seeing you around.

153
00:11:46,810 --> 00:11:47,810
Oh. Goodbye.

154
00:11:47,810 --> 00:11:48,810
Goodbye.

155
00:11:49,310 --> 00:11:51,310
I... I want your teeth.

156
00:11:51,310 --> 00:11:55,310
This place isn't a motel.
It's an insane asylum.

157
00:11:55,310 --> 00:11:57,320
- You mean that man?
- [groans]

158
00:11:57,320 --> 00:11:59,820
One minute he doesn't
want to talk to me,

159
00:11:59,820 --> 00:12:02,320
the next minute
he won't shut up.

160
00:12:02,320 --> 00:12:04,820
And then he said
he wanted my teeth.

161
00:12:04,820 --> 00:12:06,830
And you were trying
to drag me into it?

162
00:12:06,830 --> 00:12:08,830
- What do you mean?
- I heard you calling me,

163
00:12:08,830 --> 00:12:11,830
but I wasn't
coming to your rescue
wrapped in a towel.

164
00:12:11,830 --> 00:12:14,330
I didn't call you.

165
00:12:14,330 --> 00:12:18,340
I heard you.
These walls are paper thin.

166
00:12:18,340 --> 00:12:21,840
I might have said your name
a couple of times.

167
00:12:21,840 --> 00:12:26,350
It might have been
that lady's scanner too.
I can't believe how loud it is.

168
00:12:26,350 --> 00:12:29,350
Yeah. We'll move the bed.

169
00:12:29,350 --> 00:12:32,350
I just hope old Ted
doesn't snore.

170
00:12:39,860 --> 00:12:42,860
I'm definitely
doing something tomorrow
to secure these windows.

171
00:12:42,860 --> 00:12:44,860
I was out
in the parking lot
taking the stuff in,

172
00:12:44,860 --> 00:12:46,870
there was
a guy out there
staring at me,

173
00:12:46,870 --> 00:12:49,870
like he was
casing the joint
or something.

174
00:12:49,870 --> 00:12:53,870
He was probably
just checking the rates
on that sign out there.

175
00:12:53,870 --> 00:12:58,880
But you should
definitely fix the window
if it makes you feel better.

176
00:12:58,880 --> 00:13:00,880
Ah, you're probably right.

177
00:13:02,880 --> 00:13:05,380
Sorry I'm such a coward.

178
00:13:05,380 --> 00:13:06,390
What?

179
00:13:06,390 --> 00:13:09,390
Nothing.
Can you grab the top sheet?

180
00:13:09,890 --> 00:13:10,890
Yeah.

181
00:13:15,890 --> 00:13:18,400
This mattress is
just a little uneven.

182
00:13:23,900 --> 00:13:25,400
You're not a coward.

183
00:13:25,400 --> 00:13:27,410
City living
does that to people.

184
00:13:27,910 --> 00:13:31,910
If I'd been broken into
as many times as you have,
I'd have security issues too.

185
00:13:34,410 --> 00:13:35,410
Come on.
Let's go to bed.

186
00:13:35,410 --> 00:13:38,420
I'm gonna start looking
for a job tomorrow.

187
00:13:38,920 --> 00:13:40,920
Tomorrow?

188
00:13:40,920 --> 00:13:44,920
I thought that we were
going to take a couple
of days to, you know,

189
00:13:44,920 --> 00:13:49,430
settle in and...
explore, get comfortable.

190
00:13:49,930 --> 00:13:51,930
After I get a job.

191
00:13:51,930 --> 00:13:55,930
We've got to have at least
one source of income
until you make us rich.

192
00:13:55,930 --> 00:13:57,940
As a playwright?

193
00:13:57,940 --> 00:14:00,940
You're going to be
selling fried dough for
a very, very long time.

194
00:14:00,940 --> 00:14:05,940
I'm just waiting for you
to sell out and get some
of that Hollywood money.

195
00:14:05,940 --> 00:14:07,950
Don't hold your breath.

196
00:14:39,900 --> 00:14:43,400
[Ted singing]

197
00:14:43,900 --> 00:14:44,900
[thumping]

198
00:14:44,900 --> 00:14:47,400
What the--

199
00:14:47,900 --> 00:14:49,910
What's he doing
in there?

200
00:14:51,910 --> 00:14:53,410
[singing continues]

201
00:14:53,410 --> 00:14:55,410
Do you think he's okay?

202
00:14:57,410 --> 00:14:59,420
He's singing.

203
00:14:59,420 --> 00:15:00,420
What?

204
00:15:00,420 --> 00:15:01,920
Yeah.

205
00:15:01,920 --> 00:15:05,420
Oh, my God.
It's awful.

206
00:15:05,420 --> 00:15:06,420
[stops]

207
00:15:07,920 --> 00:15:11,930
- You think he heard us?
- No, I don't think so.

208
00:15:11,930 --> 00:15:14,930
What time is it?

209
00:15:14,930 --> 00:15:17,930
It's 2 a.m.
Must be his bedtime.

210
00:15:27,940 --> 00:15:32,950
[police scanner]

211
00:15:32,950 --> 00:15:36,950
I thought old people
were supposed to be quiet

212
00:15:36,950 --> 00:15:39,960
and go to bed early.

213
00:15:39,960 --> 00:15:42,460
Should we
bang on the wall?

214
00:15:42,460 --> 00:15:46,460
We don't want to seem like
jerks our first night here.

215
00:15:49,470 --> 00:15:51,470
- [rattling]
-  [singing resumes]

216
00:15:51,470 --> 00:15:52,970
This is ridiculous!

217
00:15:54,470 --> 00:15:56,470
[rattling continues]

218
00:15:56,470 --> 00:15:58,980
Oh, my God!
What is that, an earthquake?

219
00:15:58,970 --> 00:16:00,480
In Maine?

220
00:16:00,480 --> 00:16:02,980
It's just a crazy old man.

221
00:16:06,480 --> 00:16:08,480
It's freezing in here.

222
00:16:10,990 --> 00:16:12,990
[ringing]

223
00:16:16,990 --> 00:16:18,990
[ring]

224
00:16:27,500 --> 00:16:29,510
Ted! It's Rick
from next door!

225
00:16:29,510 --> 00:16:31,010
What the hell's
going on in there?

226
00:16:31,010 --> 00:16:33,510
I'm trying to sleep!

227
00:16:33,510 --> 00:16:37,510
Well, how is anybody else
supposed to sleep
with all this noise?

228
00:16:39,010 --> 00:16:40,520
It's just a freight train.

229
00:16:40,520 --> 00:16:45,020
In a few weeks,
you'll be sleeping
right through it.

230
00:16:45,020 --> 00:16:48,520
Now go back to bed.

231
00:16:53,030 --> 00:16:54,030
Sorry.

232
00:17:04,040 --> 00:17:05,540
Sorry!

233
00:17:05,540 --> 00:17:07,040
Sorry.

234
00:17:08,540 --> 00:17:11,050
Sorry.

235
00:17:11,050 --> 00:17:12,050
Damn kids.

236
00:17:24,060 --> 00:17:27,060
So much for not
looking like jerks.

237
00:17:27,060 --> 00:17:30,070
I just want
to go to bed.

238
00:17:30,070 --> 00:17:31,570
It's freezing
in here.

239
00:17:34,570 --> 00:17:37,570
Something's wrong
with that answering machine.

240
00:17:37,570 --> 00:17:41,080
I hope it wasn't my dad calling.

241
00:17:41,080 --> 00:17:43,080
It's bad enough he's all alone.

242
00:17:43,080 --> 00:17:45,080
I don't want him
worrying about me.

243
00:17:47,580 --> 00:17:50,090
It's probably
just a wrong number.

244
00:17:50,090 --> 00:17:54,590
Mrs. Farthing said that
our line's not even supposed
to be active until tomorrow.

245
00:17:57,590 --> 00:18:00,100
[police scanner]

246
00:18:18,110 --> 00:18:20,620
[silent]

247
00:18:59,520 --> 00:19:01,020
Aah!

248
00:19:01,020 --> 00:19:02,440
[gasps]

249
00:19:05,940 --> 00:19:08,450
What? What is it, honey?

250
00:19:08,450 --> 00:19:10,450
Having a nightmare?

251
00:19:10,450 --> 00:19:11,950
Yeah.

252
00:19:14,450 --> 00:19:16,960
