Now, did I hear you say
something about blood?

503
00:37:47,280 --> 00:37:49,280
Well, yeah.
It's a stain.

504
00:37:49,280 --> 00:37:51,790
It was there before,
and now it just keeps
getting bigger,

505
00:37:51,790 --> 00:37:53,290
and it's ruining
our sheets.

506
00:37:53,290 --> 00:37:55,290
Oh, that's just mold.

507
00:37:55,290 --> 00:37:58,290
No, the mold is
a whole other problem
altogether.

508
00:38:01,300 --> 00:38:04,800
That's just mold.

509
00:38:04,800 --> 00:38:07,800
Shouldn't let it
get this bad.

510
00:38:10,810 --> 00:38:14,810
Truthfully, the whole place
can do with a scrubbing.

511
00:38:15,310 --> 00:38:17,810
I'll send Stacy in,
if it's too much for you.

512
00:38:17,810 --> 00:38:21,320
No. No, thank you.
It wasn't mold. I told you.

513
00:38:21,320 --> 00:38:25,820
It was a dark reddish brown,
like blood.

514
00:38:25,820 --> 00:38:28,820
I don't see anything
like that in here.

515
00:38:28,820 --> 00:38:30,830
It must be in the bed.

516
00:38:30,830 --> 00:38:33,830
Sometimes I come home
and it's almost all dried up
and faded away,

517
00:38:33,830 --> 00:38:37,330
and then that night it's back
and it's seeping through
the sheets.

518
00:38:37,330 --> 00:38:39,830
Well, it's been
so damp lately.

519
00:38:39,830 --> 00:38:41,340
It was right here.

520
00:38:43,840 --> 00:38:45,340
Oh, my.

521
00:38:45,340 --> 00:38:48,340
That's nothing.
You should have seen it
five minutes ago.

522
00:38:51,850 --> 00:38:53,850
Oh, dear.

523
00:39:00,350 --> 00:39:02,360
- What?
- Now I remember.

524
00:39:05,360 --> 00:39:10,870
This mattress...
was in room 16

525
00:39:10,870 --> 00:39:14,370
when Mr. DeLuca
was living there.

526
00:39:16,870 --> 00:39:20,380
He was the victim
of a home invasion.

527
00:39:23,380 --> 00:39:25,880
It was terrible.

528
00:39:25,880 --> 00:39:28,380
They never caught the buggers.

529
00:39:28,380 --> 00:39:32,890
Bikers, I bet,
or maybe even Canadians.

530
00:39:34,390 --> 00:39:36,890
I don't know what
this world is coming to.

531
00:39:36,890 --> 00:39:39,890
Well, what is it
doing in here?

532
00:39:39,890 --> 00:39:43,900
We cleaned everything up
after--

533
00:39:43,900 --> 00:39:45,400
well, you know--

534
00:39:45,400 --> 00:39:50,400
and then we switched
the mattresses from
the one upstairs.

535
00:39:51,910 --> 00:39:53,910
The stain was so small

536
00:39:53,910 --> 00:39:58,410
compared to the blood
that was everywhere.

537
00:39:58,410 --> 00:40:02,920
And then this room
was never used.

538
00:40:02,920 --> 00:40:07,920
It hasn't been used
in ages, so...

539
00:40:07,920 --> 00:40:10,930
I just forgot all about it.

540
00:40:10,930 --> 00:40:12,930
That happens
when you get older.

541
00:40:12,930 --> 00:40:17,930
Sometimes your mind
just doesn't think straight.

542
00:40:17,930 --> 00:40:21,940
I am so terribly sorry.

543
00:40:23,940 --> 00:40:26,440
I'll call
the Bedding Warehouse
right away

544
00:40:26,440 --> 00:40:30,950
and have them haul
this evil thing away

545
00:40:30,950 --> 00:40:32,950
and bring you
a brand-new one.

546
00:40:32,950 --> 00:40:34,450
Thank you.

547
00:40:37,950 --> 00:40:41,460
Don't thank me.

548
00:40:41,460 --> 00:40:45,460
I can't believe I made
such a terrible mistake.

549
00:40:45,960 --> 00:40:48,960
And you've been
sleeping on this
all this time?

550
00:40:48,960 --> 00:40:50,470
You should have
come and told me.

551
00:40:50,460 --> 00:40:52,470
How quickly do you think
the new mattress
could be here?

552
00:40:52,970 --> 00:40:54,470
I really don't want
Rick to see this.

553
00:40:54,970 --> 00:40:58,470
He gets pretty upset about
things like home invasions.

554
00:40:58,470 --> 00:41:01,480
Oh, they come pretty fast.

555
00:41:01,480 --> 00:41:03,480
I'm sure they'll be
in and out of here

556
00:41:03,480 --> 00:41:06,480
before your boyfriend
gets back from work.

557
00:41:06,480 --> 00:41:08,480
Well, that's the problem.
He works from home,

558
00:41:08,480 --> 00:41:12,490
so I have
no way of knowing
when he'll be here.

559
00:41:12,490 --> 00:41:14,990
Oh?

560
00:41:14,990 --> 00:41:18,490
I thought he went out
and got himself a real job.

561
00:41:18,490 --> 00:41:21,000
Playwriting!

562
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:24,000
Still, he keeps
pretty regular hours,

563
00:41:24,000 --> 00:41:26,500
9:30, 10:00,

564
00:41:26,500 --> 00:41:29,500
then he comes home
just before you do.

565
00:41:31,510 --> 00:41:33,010
Really?

566
00:41:33,010 --> 00:41:39,010
I am not sticking my nose
in where it doesn't belong.

567
00:41:39,010 --> 00:41:41,520
Really, dear.

568
00:41:41,520 --> 00:41:45,520
I just like to keep
an eye on things.

569
00:41:45,520 --> 00:41:46,520
Of course.

570
00:41:50,020 --> 00:41:54,030
Well, I'll go call
the mattress folks.

571
00:42:25,980 --> 00:42:27,980
[sighs]

572
00:42:27,980 --> 00:42:30,480
You're home early.

573
00:42:30,480 --> 00:42:31,980
What are you doing home?

574
00:42:31,980 --> 00:42:35,990
Somebody called in
a bomb scare
at the library.

575
00:42:36,490 --> 00:42:37,990
What's all this?

576
00:42:37,990 --> 00:42:43,990
Mrs. Farthing said that they
have to change the mattresses
every certain number of years.

577
00:42:43,990 --> 00:42:46,500
It's some state regulation
or something.

578
00:42:49,500 --> 00:42:51,000
I see you cleaned.

579
00:42:51,500 --> 00:42:53,000
Just a little.

580
00:42:54,510 --> 00:42:57,010
The place just needed
a little cleaning up.

581
00:42:57,010 --> 00:42:58,510
I was gonna do it.

582
00:42:58,510 --> 00:43:02,510
Hey, what's all this
"You're home early" stuff?

583
00:43:02,510 --> 00:43:06,020
Mrs. Farthing was telling me
about your daily routine.

584
00:43:06,020 --> 00:43:09,020
Nosy old farts just can't
mind their own business!

585
00:43:09,520 --> 00:43:11,020
Where do you go
all day?

586
00:43:11,020 --> 00:43:14,530
I take walks.
You know that.

587
00:43:16,030 --> 00:43:18,530
Sometimes
I stop into this bar.

588
00:43:18,530 --> 00:43:22,030
Oh, that I can tell.
You smell like a brewery.

589
00:43:22,030 --> 00:43:25,540
You want me to stay cooped up
in this little place all day?

590
00:43:27,540 --> 00:43:31,040
I need go out someplace
where I can sit,

591
00:43:31,040 --> 00:43:34,550
think, write.

592
00:43:34,550 --> 00:43:36,550
There are such things
as libraries.

593
00:43:36,550 --> 00:43:39,050
I'm not going to the place
where you work to write.

594
00:43:39,050 --> 00:43:43,050
I didn't mean my library.
There are two other branches.

595
00:43:43,050 --> 00:43:45,560
But, of course,
they don't serve beer.

596
00:43:47,060 --> 00:43:48,560
Why are you doing this?

597
00:43:48,560 --> 00:43:53,060
Is it because I didn't do
some of my household chores?

598
00:43:53,060 --> 00:43:56,070
I'm sorry.
Let's just forget it.

599
00:44:01,570 --> 00:44:06,080
I'm trying to
adjust to, you know,
things in this apartment.

600
00:44:06,080 --> 00:44:07,580
And I...

601
00:44:09,580 --> 00:44:11,580
I don't know.

602
00:44:11,580 --> 00:44:14,590
I'm not comfortable
here and...

603
00:44:14,590 --> 00:44:18,590
I need to go out and
get comfortable to write.

604
00:44:18,590 --> 00:44:20,090
You don't have to
explain yourself to me.

605
00:44:20,090 --> 00:44:24,090
Just don't drink
all of my earnings away.

606
00:44:24,090 --> 00:44:25,600
Fine! I'll get a job!

607
00:44:25,600 --> 00:44:29,100
I was joking, okay?
I don't want you
to get a job.

608
00:44:29,100 --> 00:44:31,600
That would defeat
our whole purpose of--

609
00:44:33,100 --> 00:44:34,610
Hey, what's going on?
What's going on?

610
00:44:34,610 --> 00:44:37,610
Sorry.
I'm sorry.

611
00:44:37,610 --> 00:44:39,610
I'm just not
feeling well.

612
00:44:39,610 --> 00:44:44,120
Hey, no, no.
Just lay down.

613
00:44:44,110 --> 00:44:45,120
It's all right.

614
00:44:50,620 --> 00:44:52,620
You're not seeing
someone else,
are you?

615
00:44:52,620 --> 00:44:55,130
[chuckles]
Not the way you're thinking.

616
00:44:55,130 --> 00:44:57,130
What does that mean?

617
00:45:00,130 --> 00:45:02,130
Uh, no, it's, uh--

618
00:45:04,130 --> 00:45:07,140
Nah. It's--
I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

619
00:45:07,140 --> 00:45:10,640
No. I have been hanging out
at this bar, yes,

620
00:45:11,140 --> 00:45:13,140
with a guy and writer--

621
00:45:13,640 --> 00:45:15,650
that writer-director guy.

622
00:45:17,150 --> 00:45:20,650
He's a writer-director.
We have a lot in common.

623
00:45:20,650 --> 00:45:22,650
[mumbles]

624
00:45:24,150 --> 00:45:26,660
At least
you're making friends.

625
00:45:32,160 --> 00:45:33,660
Yeah.

626
00:46:09,500 --> 00:46:12,000
You don't have
to stay here
with me all day.

627
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:17,510
Oh, no. I'm just going to try
to get some writing done
in the laundry room.

628
00:46:17,510 --> 00:46:19,010
You rest.

629
00:46:36,030 --> 00:46:39,030
Cleanliness
is next to godliness.

630
00:47:00,550 --> 00:47:03,050
[loud rattling]

631
00:47:28,080 --> 00:47:29,080
What's wrong?

632
00:47:29,080 --> 00:47:31,580
I just remembered
I need to go out.
Do you need anything?

633
00:47:31,580 --> 00:47:35,090
- Where are you going to go?
- I need to meet Phil.

634
00:47:35,090 --> 00:47:38,590
- Who's Phil?
- That writer-actor guy
I told you about.

635
00:47:38,590 --> 00:47:41,090
He was going to have a meeting
with a big producer and--

636
00:47:41,090 --> 00:47:43,090
- Oh, yeah?
- He might be able
to help me out.

637
00:47:43,090 --> 00:47:45,100
Okay. Well, can you
call him or something?

638
00:47:45,100 --> 00:47:48,100
I don't have his number.
Look, I won't be long.

639
00:47:48,100 --> 00:47:50,100
The laundry is almost done.

640
00:47:50,100 --> 00:47:52,600
I'll take it out
when I get back.

641
00:47:52,600 --> 00:47:54,100
Okay, okay.

642
00:47:54,100 --> 00:47:56,610
Can I take the car?

643
00:47:56,610 --> 00:47:58,610
- Yeah, of course.
- Thanks.

644
00:47:58,610 --> 00:48:00,610
Rick, can you take the--

645
00:48:14,120 --> 00:48:16,630
[ringing]

646
00:48:17,630 --> 00:48:19,630
- Hello.
- [static]

647
00:48:19,630 --> 00:48:22,630
- Hello? I can't hear you.
- [woman] This is the end--

648
00:48:22,630 --> 00:48:25,140
[garbled]
Leave here now--

649
00:48:26,640 --> 00:48:29,140
- Hello?
- Hello?

650
00:48:29,140 --> 00:48:32,140
- Oh, Claudette.
- Can you hear me all right?

651
00:48:32,140 --> 00:48:34,650
I can now. There was
a lot of static on the line.

652
00:48:34,640 --> 00:48:36,150
How are you feeling?

653
00:48:36,650 --> 00:48:38,650
Awful.

654
00:48:38,650 --> 00:48:40,650
I just-- I can't
shake this thing.

655
00:48:40,650 --> 00:48:42,650
It's been three days,
and I don't feel any better.

656
00:48:42,650 --> 00:48:44,650
If anything, I feel worse.

657
00:48:44,650 --> 00:48:46,660
Have you gone to a doctor?

658
00:48:46,660 --> 00:48:49,160
No, not yet, but if
I don't get better soon,
I'm going to have to.

659
00:48:49,160 --> 00:48:51,160
You really should
see someone.

660
00:48:51,160 --> 00:48:53,160
I know,
but I can't afford it.

661
00:48:53,660 --> 00:48:55,670
I'm supporting us both
right now.

662
00:48:56,170 --> 00:48:58,170
You don't have insurance?

663
00:48:58,170 --> 00:49:01,170
No. My policy
from the last job ran out,

664
00:49:01,170 --> 00:49:05,680
and I haven't been
at the library long enough
to get a new one.

665
00:49:05,680 --> 00:49:09,180
[sighs]
You know, I didn't want
to bring this up,

666
00:49:09,180 --> 00:49:10,680
- but...
- What?

667
00:49:10,680 --> 00:49:13,680
The director's
being a bitch.

668
00:49:13,680 --> 00:49:17,690
She says that since you're
a new hire and you've been
out for a couple days now,

669
00:49:17,690 --> 00:49:20,190
that you have to come back
to work with a doctor's note

670
00:49:20,190 --> 00:49:23,690
or else they're going
to have to let you go.

671
00:49:23,690 --> 00:49:25,200
I'm sorry.

672
00:49:25,200 --> 00:49:27,200
That's okay.
I understand.

673
00:49:27,200 --> 00:49:31,200
I tried to explain to her
how great you are.

674
00:49:31,200 --> 00:49:33,700
That's all right.

675
00:49:33,700 --> 00:49:36,710
I'll try to get a good night's
sleep tonight and see if I can
get in there tomorrow.

676
00:49:37,210 --> 00:49:38,210
You sound terrible.

677
00:49:38,210 --> 00:49:41,210
Why don't I try
to find you a doctor?

678
00:49:41,210 --> 00:49:43,210
No, that's okay.

679
00:49:43,210 --> 00:49:45,720
You know, I'm not being
totally selfless.

680
00:49:45,720 --> 00:49:49,220
If we lose you,
I'll have to do all
of the work again myself.

681
00:49:49,220 --> 00:49:52,720
Well, who do you see?

682
00:49:52,720 --> 00:49:55,230
My doctor can only take
people through HMOs.

683
00:49:55,230 --> 00:49:58,730
I'll see if I can find
some sort of clinic
or something, okay?

684
00:49:59,230 --> 00:50:01,230
That would be great.
Thanks, Claudette.

685
00:50:01,230 --> 00:50:03,230
It's my pleasure.

686
00:50:03,230 --> 00:50:06,740
I'll let you
get some rest now.
Take care.

687
00:50:06,740 --> 00:50:09,240
- Bye.
- Okay, thanks. Bye.

688
00:50:44,770 --> 00:50:45,780
That's it?

689
00:50:49,280 --> 00:50:51,280
One page?

690
00:50:56,790 --> 00:50:58,790
[sighs]

691
00:51:23,310 --> 00:51:26,820
Sorry I was out so late.
Phil and I had a lot
to talk about.

692
00:51:31,820 --> 00:51:36,330
You didn't have to do that.
I said I would bring that
laundry in when I came back.

693
00:51:36,830 --> 00:51:39,830
I didn't want Ted rummaging
through my underwear.

694
00:51:42,330 --> 00:51:44,840
How did your friend's meeting
with the producer go?

695
00:51:44,830 --> 00:51:47,840
Pretty well.
He said pretty well.

696
00:51:47,840 --> 00:51:51,340
Is there anything in it
for you?

697
00:51:51,340 --> 00:51:55,350
Maybe. I've got to get some
writing samples together.

698
00:51:55,350 --> 00:51:57,850
You have anything?

699
00:51:57,850 --> 00:52:01,850
Yeah. What do you think
I've been working on
this whole time?

700
00:52:01,850 --> 00:52:03,850
One page.

701
00:52:03,850 --> 00:52:05,860
There's more to it
than that.

702
00:52:05,860 --> 00:52:08,360
What have you been doing,
going through my stuff
without telling me?

703
00:52:08,860 --> 00:52:11,360
I didn't read anything.
I just looked at it.

704
00:52:11,360 --> 00:52:13,360
I know I shouldn't have.
I'm sorry.

705
00:52:13,360 --> 00:52:14,360
I can't take this.

706
00:52:16,370 --> 00:52:18,870
I can't work like this.
I get no support from you!

707
00:52:18,870 --> 00:52:23,870
No support?
I've done nothing but
support you since we got here!

708
00:52:23,870 --> 00:52:27,880
That's not what I mean.
I'm sorry.

709
00:52:27,880 --> 00:52:31,380
It's just
in this little room and--

710
00:52:31,380 --> 00:52:32,880
I can't concentrate.

711
00:52:35,890 --> 00:52:38,390
And I feel like I'm
going insane in here.

712
00:52:38,390 --> 00:52:40,890
Why don't you talk to me
about this stuff?

713
00:52:40,890 --> 00:52:44,390
You used to tell me everything.
Now you just clam up.

714
00:52:50,400 --> 00:52:53,900
I just need
to be able think.

715
00:52:53,900 --> 00:52:55,910
I can't think
in this apartment,

716
00:52:56,410 --> 00:52:58,910
and I can't think with you
hassling me all the time.

717
00:52:58,910 --> 00:53:01,910
I didn't realize
I was hassling you.

718
00:53:06,920 --> 00:53:08,920
You don't understand.

719
00:53:08,920 --> 00:53:11,920
I mean, you're not
a creative person.

720
00:53:11,920 --> 00:53:14,920
Writing is not like
sitting at a desk,

721
00:53:14,920 --> 00:53:17,430
typing in names
into a card catalog.

722
00:53:17,930 --> 00:53:20,430
I need to...

723
00:53:20,430 --> 00:53:21,930
I need to concentrate.

724
00:53:22,430 --> 00:53:25,440
Maybe if you had some dreams
of your own, you'd understand.

725
00:53:25,440 --> 00:53:27,940
Dreams of my own?

726
00:53:27,940 --> 00:53:29,940
I have dreams of my own.

727
00:53:29,940 --> 00:53:33,440
I just put them all on hold,
so I could help you
realize yours!

728
00:53:35,450 --> 00:53:39,950
And I took all the same
creative classes
as you did in college.

729
00:53:39,950 --> 00:53:42,950
The only difference is
that I actually graduated!

730
00:53:42,950 --> 00:53:45,460
You took the safe route,
while I actually
went out and did stuff.

731
00:53:45,460 --> 00:53:46,960
And look where it got you.

732
00:53:46,960 --> 00:53:49,960
You're an assistant
at a library in the
middle of nowhere.

733
00:53:49,960 --> 00:53:51,960
That job and all
the others before it

734
00:53:51,960 --> 00:53:53,960
are what's made
this trip possible.

735
00:53:53,960 --> 00:53:55,970
That's what paid
for the car,

736
00:53:55,970 --> 00:53:58,970
and that's what paid for
the computer that you're
supposed to be writing on,

737
00:53:58,970 --> 00:54:01,470
not to mention all the beer
you've been drinking.

738
00:54:01,470 --> 00:54:04,980
Don't worry.
I won't forget that!
How could I ever forget that?

739
00:54:09,980 --> 00:54:11,980
What is it?

740
00:54:13,480 --> 00:54:15,990
I just don't feel so good.

741
00:54:20,490 --> 00:54:22,990
I'm sorry, Rick.
I just--

742
00:54:25,500 --> 00:54:28,000
I don't know why
we're fighting so much.

743
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:35,510
You're really drunk,
and I feel like death.

744
00:54:35,510 --> 00:54:38,510
Could we please just try
to work this out tomorrow?

745
00:54:44,510 --> 00:54:46,020
No.

746
00:54:47,520 --> 00:54:49,020
I'm leaving.

747
00:54:49,020 --> 00:54:52,520
Come on. Please?

748
00:54:52,520 --> 00:54:55,030
Just come to bed.

749
00:54:55,020 --> 00:54:58,030
I can't stay here anymore.

750
00:54:58,030 --> 00:55:00,530
It's driving me nuts.

751
00:55:03,030 --> 00:55:04,530
Well, maybe I can just
work a few extra hours,

752
00:55:05,030 --> 00:55:07,540
and we can get a place
that's bigger.

753
00:55:07,540 --> 00:55:10,040
I'm tired of living
in the middle of nowhere!

754
00:55:10,540 --> 00:55:12,040
There's nothing here!

755
00:55:14,040 --> 00:55:18,050
I've been trying
to tell you for days now,

756
00:55:18,050 --> 00:55:19,050
but you've been so sick.

757
00:55:19,050 --> 00:55:22,050
Tell me what?
Tell me! What?

758
00:55:25,560 --> 00:55:28,060
Phil made a deal
with that producer.

759
00:55:28,060 --> 00:55:33,560
He's going out to L.A.,
and he's going to be
developing a TV show.

760
00:55:33,560 --> 00:55:35,070
I might be able
to get on board.

761
00:55:35,060 --> 00:55:37,070
It's not 100%,
but once he gets in,

762
00:55:37,070 --> 00:55:39,070
I'll probably be able
to get a job.

763
00:55:39,070 --> 00:55:41,570
L.A.?

764
00:55:41,570 --> 00:55:44,070
You hate L.A.!

765
00:55:44,570 --> 00:55:46,080
And TV?

766
00:55:46,080 --> 00:55:48,080
Whatever happened
to never selling out?

767
00:55:48,080 --> 00:55:50,080
It's a chance to get
my foot in the door.

768
00:55:50,080 --> 00:55:53,080
- I'm not getting any younger.
- God! So that's it?

769
00:55:53,080 --> 00:55:57,590
So that's it. This was
just a whole waste of time.

770
00:55:57,590 --> 00:55:59,090
We're moving to L.A.?

771
00:55:59,090 --> 00:56:02,590
No. Just me.

772
00:56:02,590 --> 00:56:06,600
I need time alone
to write and...

773
00:56:06,600 --> 00:56:09,600
Well, Phil's going to need
a roommate out there.

774
00:56:12,100 --> 00:56:15,100
And what am I
supposed to do?

775
00:56:15,100 --> 00:56:16,110
Stay here.

776
00:56:16,110 --> 00:56:19,110
You seem to be doing all right.

777
00:56:19,110 --> 00:56:21,610
There's always New York.
You can go back there.

778
00:56:25,110 --> 00:56:27,120
So it's over?

779
00:56:27,620 --> 00:56:30,120
You don't love me anymore?

780
00:56:34,120 --> 00:56:37,630
It's just not good times
for us right now.

781
00:56:37,630 --> 00:56:40,130
I mean, uh...

782
00:56:43,630 --> 00:56:46,640
My career
and my life,

783
00:56:46,640 --> 00:56:52,640
I mean, it's too
up in the air for...

784
00:56:52,640 --> 00:56:55,650
us to have got so tied down
like we got here.

785
00:56:56,150 --> 00:56:57,650
I've got to think
of my future.

786
00:56:57,650 --> 00:57:00,150
I've got to think
of my writing.

787
00:57:00,150 --> 00:57:02,150
I need to be able to write,

788
00:57:02,150 --> 00:57:06,160
go and write
and experience living.

789
00:57:06,160 --> 00:57:10,160
Oh, yeah, by living in
Hollywood and getting drunk
all the time with Phil?

790
00:57:10,660 --> 00:57:14,160
[sobbing]

791
00:57:14,160 --> 00:57:19,670
It beats slaving away
at some nine-to-five job,

792
00:57:19,670 --> 00:57:22,170
worrying about
credit card payments.

793
00:57:25,170 --> 00:57:27,680
Okay.

794
00:57:27,680 --> 00:57:31,680
Okay, fine.

795
00:57:31,680 --> 00:57:33,680
So when do you go?

796
00:57:33,680 --> 00:57:35,690
Tonight.

797
00:57:35,690 --> 00:57:38,190
What?

798
00:57:38,190 --> 00:57:42,190
I said I've been trying
to tell you for days!

799
00:57:50,200 --> 00:57:53,700
I just came to pick up
a few things,

800
00:57:53,700 --> 00:57:58,210
and then I've got
to go meet Phil.

801
00:57:58,210 --> 00:58:02,710
He and Stacy got into a fight,
and she kicked him out.

802
00:58:02,710 --> 00:58:04,210
Wait a minute.

803
00:58:04,210 --> 00:58:08,220
The housekeeper's boyfriend?
That's your friend Phil?

804
00:58:08,220 --> 00:58:10,220
Yeah. He's a nice guy.

805
00:58:11,720 --> 00:58:13,220
You can't be serious.

806
00:58:13,220 --> 00:58:15,730
You're 34 years old.
What's happened to you?

807
00:58:19,730 --> 00:58:21,230
Nothing.

808
00:58:21,230 --> 00:58:23,730
I just gotta
get out of here.

809
00:58:23,730 --> 00:58:27,740
So you're just
abandoning me here?

810
00:58:27,740 --> 00:58:30,740
The rent is due
in two days. I either
have to move out tomorrow

811
00:58:30,740 --> 00:58:34,740
or pay it for another month
and stay here by myself.

812
00:58:34,740 --> 00:58:36,750
Take my advice: Move out.

813
00:58:36,750 --> 00:58:40,250
Where am I supposed to go?

814
00:58:40,250 --> 00:58:42,750
This is so sudden,
and I'm really sick.

815
00:58:42,750 --> 00:58:47,760
You have credit cards.
You've got a job.
You'll be fine.

816
00:58:48,260 --> 00:58:52,260
[sobbing]
Why are you
doing this to me?

817
00:58:55,260 --> 00:58:58,770
- I don't know.
- No.

818
00:58:58,770 --> 00:59:01,770
- Goodbye, Kathryn.
- No, no.

819
00:59:01,770 --> 00:59:03,770
No, Rick, no. Please.

820
00:59:03,770 --> 00:59:05,780
Please, Rick, please.

821
00:59:09,280 --> 00:59:11,280
I'll... call you.

822
00:59:16,790 --> 00:59:19,290
Thanks for getting
the laundry.

823
00:59:19,290 --> 00:59:21,790
No, Rick. Rick, Rick!

824
00:59:21,790 --> 00:59:23,290
Rick, please!

825
00:59:23,290 --> 00:59:27,300
No, no, no, no!
[sobbing]

826
00:59:39,810 --> 00:59:41,810
[coughing]

827
01:00:21,520 --> 01:00:23,520
[phone rings]

828
01:00:26,520 --> 01:00:29,030
[ring]

829
01:00:32,530 --> 01:00:34,530
[ring]

830
01:00:34,530 --> 01:00:36,030
[answering machine beeps]

831
01:00:36,030 --> 01:00:38,540
[Claudette]
Kathryn,
it's the library again.

832
01:00:39,040 --> 01:00:41,040
I've been calling you
for a few days now,

833
01:00:41,040 --> 01:00:44,040
and I'm getting
really worried.

834
01:00:44,040 --> 01:00:45,540
Please pick up, Kathryn.

835
01:00:45,540 --> 01:00:48,040
I don't know if I should
come over there

836
01:00:48,040 --> 01:00:50,050
or call the police or what.

837
01:00:51,550 --> 01:00:54,550
Please give me a call
at the library or at home.

838
01:00:54,550 --> 01:00:56,550
It doesn't matter what time.

839
01:00:56,550 --> 01:01:00,060
Just let me know you're alive.

840
01:01:00,060 --> 01:01:01,020
[hangs up]

841
01:01:04,060 --> 01:01:06,560
- [knocking]
- [Claudette] Hello!

842
01:01:06,560 --> 01:01:08,060
Kathryn?

843
01:01:09,070 --> 01:01:10,570
- Hello?
- Who is it?

844
01:01:10,570 --> 01:01:11,980
Kathryn, is that you?

845
01:01:13,490 --> 01:01:15,490
[knocking]

846
01:01:15,490 --> 01:01:19,490
Hello? It's me.
It's Claudette. Open up.

847
01:01:19,490 --> 01:01:22,000
Oh, thank God!
You're alive!

848
01:01:21,990 --> 01:01:25,000
I just-- Oh!

849
01:01:25,000 --> 01:01:27,000
What happened to you?

850
01:01:27,000 --> 01:01:29,500
Um, I'm so sorry,
Claudette.

851
01:01:29,500 --> 01:01:33,010
I... I just woke up.
I was going to give you a call.

852
01:01:33,010 --> 01:01:35,510
I was gonna listen
to your messages.

853
01:01:35,510 --> 01:01:39,010
Give me a call? I've been
trying to get in touch
with you for a week.

854
01:01:39,010 --> 01:01:43,020
- What?
- I've been calling you
since last Thursday.

855
01:01:43,020 --> 01:01:45,020
Wait. What day is today?

856
01:01:45,020 --> 01:01:47,520
- It's Tuesday.
- Tuesday?

857
01:01:51,020 --> 01:01:53,530
I lost a whole week.

858
01:01:53,530 --> 01:01:54,530
Oh, God.

859
01:01:57,030 --> 01:01:59,030
Oh, God.

860
01:01:59,030 --> 01:02:02,540
You know, I can't believe
I've been so stupid.

861
01:02:02,540 --> 01:02:06,040
You're so together at work, and
you've got those fancy clothes.

862
01:02:06,040 --> 01:02:09,040
I didn't think
that there was a problem.

863
01:02:09,040 --> 01:02:11,040
- That eye.
- What? What problem?

864
01:02:11,040 --> 01:02:15,050
Come on. I'm not stupid.
I'm from Maine.

865
01:02:15,050 --> 01:02:17,050
Our winters
are long and cold.

866
01:02:17,050 --> 01:02:20,550
- I know about this.
- Wait. You think I'm a drunk?

867
01:02:20,550 --> 01:02:22,060
- Well--
- [chuckles]

868
01:02:22,050 --> 01:02:24,560
No, I mean, I'm just--

869
01:02:24,560 --> 01:02:26,060
If you admit
that you have a problem,

870
01:02:26,560 --> 01:02:29,060
then we can do something
about it and you'll get better.

871
01:02:29,060 --> 01:02:31,560
I don't know. Maybe you can
even get your old job back.

872
01:02:34,070 --> 01:02:36,070
Oh, she fired me?

873
01:02:36,070 --> 01:02:41,070
Well, you know,
I... I warned you.

874
01:02:41,070 --> 01:02:43,080
Look, Claudette,
I know what this
must look like,

875
01:02:43,080 --> 01:02:47,080
but I'm not an alcoholic
or a junkie

876
01:02:47,080 --> 01:02:50,580
or whatever this
looks like to you.

877
01:02:50,580 --> 01:02:52,590
I-- I just, um...

878
01:02:52,590 --> 01:02:57,590
I've just been
really sick and...

879
01:02:57,590 --> 01:02:59,590
and Rick left me.

880
01:02:59,590 --> 01:03:02,100
Oh, I...

881
01:03:02,090 --> 01:03:04,100
I didn't know.
I'm sorry.

882
01:03:04,100 --> 01:03:06,600
Yeah, he just left.

883
01:03:06,600 --> 01:03:08,600
It came out of nowhere.

884
01:03:08,600 --> 01:03:10,100
But you know, maybe--

885
01:03:10,100 --> 01:03:14,110
I mean, if he's
the kind of guy who's
going to do that to you,

886
01:03:14,110 --> 01:03:15,610
you don't need him.

887
01:03:15,610 --> 01:03:17,610
Rick didn't do this.
He would never.

888
01:03:17,610 --> 01:03:21,110
- He's not like that.
- Well, then who did?

889
01:03:21,110 --> 01:03:24,120
Well, I don't know.
I just woke up with it.

890
01:03:24,120 --> 01:03:26,620
I mean, I must have
fallen out of bed or--

891
01:03:26,620 --> 01:03:28,120
[sighs]
Okay, look.

892
01:03:28,620 --> 01:03:31,120
I've got to go back to work.
I just, um...

893
01:03:31,120 --> 01:03:36,130
You know, I have some numbers
of some doctors. Would you
just take them and--

894
01:03:36,130 --> 01:03:40,630
No. Thank you very much,
but I told you
I really don't think--

895
01:03:40,630 --> 01:03:46,140
It doesn't have to be now.
Just take them and call me
if you need anything.

896
01:03:46,140 --> 01:03:49,640
- Okay.
- How are you set for money?

897
01:03:49,640 --> 01:03:52,150
I have another check
coming from my last week
of work, don't I?

898
01:03:52,140 --> 01:03:55,650
Right.
They'll mail it to you.

899
01:03:55,650 --> 01:03:58,150
But is that enough?

900
01:03:58,150 --> 01:04:02,150
Well, I have some money
in the bank, and I have--

901
01:04:02,150 --> 01:04:06,160
Oh, the rent was due days ago.
[laughs]

902
01:04:06,160 --> 01:04:09,160
Well, I'll be fine, Claudette.
Thank you so much for coming by.

903
01:04:09,160 --> 01:04:12,160
Oh, no. I was just--
You had me all worried.

904
01:04:12,160 --> 01:04:13,170
Thanks.

905
01:04:13,170 --> 01:04:16,670
No. Look, just please--

906
01:04:16,670 --> 01:04:19,670
Oh, listen. Would you--

907
01:04:20,670 --> 01:04:23,180
Would you take
these back for me?

908
01:04:23,180 --> 01:04:25,680
I can't really afford
any overdue fines.

909
01:04:25,680 --> 01:04:29,680
Yes. Please just call me
if you need anything.

910
01:04:29,680 --> 01:04:31,180
- I will. Thanks.
- Okay.

911
01:04:31,180 --> 01:04:33,190
- Okay, bye.
- Okay, bye.

912
01:05:02,210 --> 01:05:03,720
[knocking]

913
01:05:08,720 --> 01:05:10,220
Yes? Can I help you?

914
01:05:10,220 --> 01:05:12,220
Hi, Mrs. Farthing.

915
01:05:14,230 --> 01:05:17,730
It's Kathryn Bennett
from unit 13.

916
01:05:17,730 --> 01:05:20,730
Unit 13 is rented.
You'll have to go
somewhere else.

917
01:05:20,730 --> 01:05:24,740
No, it's me, Kathryn.
I already live in 13.

918
01:05:26,240 --> 01:05:29,740
Oh, it is you.
I didn't even recognize you.

919
01:05:29,740 --> 01:05:32,750
I'm sorry this is so late.
I've been sick.

920
01:05:32,750 --> 01:05:36,250
I hadn't realized
it was that time already.

921
01:05:36,250 --> 01:05:38,250
I was wondering
where you were.

922
01:05:38,250 --> 01:05:41,250
I haven't seen
that man of yours
around lately either.

923
01:05:41,250 --> 01:05:43,760
He moved out.

924
01:05:43,760 --> 01:05:45,760
Oh, I see.

925
01:05:45,760 --> 01:05:48,260
Why don't you come in
and rest for just a minute?

926
01:05:48,260 --> 01:05:50,260
Oh, you look terrible.

927
01:05:50,760 --> 01:05:52,770
- No, I'm all right.
- I insist.

928
01:05:52,770 --> 01:05:54,270
Oh, my goodness! Oh!

929
01:05:54,270 --> 01:05:57,270
- You all right, dear?
- I'm sorry.

930
01:05:57,770 --> 01:05:59,270
Come in.

931
01:06:29,800 --> 01:06:31,300
Oh.

932
01:06:31,300 --> 01:06:33,810
Shh. Your head is getting pink.
You have to be careful.

933
01:06:33,810 --> 01:06:35,310
Your skin is so fair.

934
01:06:35,310 --> 01:06:38,810
You can get a sunburn
even though it's not summer.

935
01:06:39,310 --> 01:06:40,310
Oh.

936
01:06:42,820 --> 01:06:44,320
Oh, thank you.

937
01:06:46,820 --> 01:06:48,820
I'm sorry the room
is such a mess.

938
01:06:48,820 --> 01:06:51,820
Oh, it's not so bad.
It just needed
a little picking up.

939
01:06:51,820 --> 01:06:54,330
It's hard keeping up
with all that mold.

940
01:06:54,330 --> 01:06:58,830
You know, Mrs. Farthing said
she thinks that's what's
made me so sick.

941
01:06:58,830 --> 01:07:00,830
Maybe.

942
01:07:00,830 --> 01:07:02,840
What, you don't think so?

943
01:07:04,840 --> 01:07:08,840
Whenever I'm in there,
I feel something.

944
01:07:08,840 --> 01:07:13,350
It's like the room
is creepy, evil.

945
01:07:13,350 --> 01:07:15,850
Do you know what
I'm talking about?

946
01:07:15,850 --> 01:07:18,850
The place has always seemed
a little depressing to me.

947
01:07:18,850 --> 01:07:23,360
It's like all the unhappiness
that you experienced in there
is still lingering.

948
01:07:23,360 --> 01:07:26,360
It's like it's haunted
by bad feelings.

949
01:07:29,360 --> 01:07:30,860
You think I'm crazy.

950
01:07:30,860 --> 01:07:33,370
No, I don't.
I know what you mean.

951
01:07:33,370 --> 01:07:35,870
Well, I can put some
herbs and stuff in there

952
01:07:35,870 --> 01:07:38,370
that are supposed to cleanse
the spirit of the room.

953
01:07:38,370 --> 01:07:40,870
- If nothing else,
it smells nice.
- Oh, that's okay.

954
01:07:40,870 --> 01:07:43,380
Actually, I already did.

955
01:07:43,380 --> 01:07:45,380
Thank you.

956
01:07:45,380 --> 01:07:47,380
Why are you being
so nice to me?

957
01:07:47,380 --> 01:07:49,380
I never thought
you liked us very much.

958
01:07:49,380 --> 01:07:50,380
I'm sorry.

959
01:07:50,380 --> 01:07:54,890
You know I was having
man troubles of my own.

960
01:07:54,890 --> 01:07:55,890
Sorry.

961
01:07:55,890 --> 01:07:57,890
Oh, it's okay.
It's over now.

962
01:07:57,890 --> 01:08:00,890
He's gone.
I'm better off.

963
01:08:00,890 --> 01:08:01,890
[Mrs. Farthing]
That's enough, Stacy.

964
01:08:02,390 --> 01:08:06,900
We have to let this pretty
little lady get her rest.

965
01:08:06,900 --> 01:08:08,900
- See you later.
- Thanks.

966
01:08:09,900 --> 01:08:11,900
How are you feeling?

967
01:08:11,900 --> 01:08:14,910
- A little better, thanks.
- Well, you look it.

968
01:08:14,910 --> 01:08:18,910
I know how much
you like to read,
so I brought you the paper.

969
01:08:18,910 --> 01:08:23,420
And these are some of the books
that the man who used to live
in your unit wrote.

970
01:08:23,420 --> 01:08:25,920
He wrote a few of these
all while he was living here.

971
01:08:26,420 --> 01:08:31,420
They're all about the lives
of various local celebrities
and politicians.

972
01:08:31,420 --> 01:08:33,430
Eww!

973
01:08:33,430 --> 01:08:35,930
I didn't mean
to bring out that one.

974
01:08:35,930 --> 01:08:37,930
So it was Peter Warren.

975
01:08:37,930 --> 01:08:40,930
That's his real name,
supposedly.

976
01:08:40,930 --> 01:08:45,440
Lord knows why he decided
to use it for this trash.

977
01:08:45,440 --> 01:08:50,940
Once he started making money
writing this nonsense,
he moved out of here.

978
01:08:50,940 --> 01:08:53,450
He's a really famous writer.

979
01:08:53,450 --> 01:08:56,950
I wouldn't know.
I don't read
that sort of trash.

980
01:08:56,950 --> 01:09:00,450
And neither should you.
You're sick enough as it is.

981
01:09:00,450 --> 01:09:03,460
Stick to his good ones.

982
01:09:03,460 --> 01:09:05,460
They're all true stories,
you know.

983
01:09:05,460 --> 01:09:07,460
Everyone should read.

984
01:09:07,960 --> 01:09:10,460
Helps you
to keep an open mind.

985
01:09:26,980 --> 01:09:29,480
- All done!
- Oh, thank you.

986
01:09:29,480 --> 01:09:31,980
I'll have to
make it up to you sometime
when I'm feeling better.

987
01:09:31,980 --> 01:09:33,490
Forget it.

988
01:09:33,990 --> 01:09:36,490
- Did Mrs. Farthing
give you those?
- Yeah.

989
01:09:36,490 --> 01:09:37,990
Pretty seedy, huh?

990
01:09:37,990 --> 01:09:39,990
I didn't know Peter Warren
wrote this kind of stuff.

991
01:09:39,990 --> 01:09:41,490
I don't think
he brags about it.

992
01:09:41,490 --> 01:09:44,000
You can see why
he used a fake name.

993
01:09:44,000 --> 01:09:45,500
I've never heard
of half these people.

994
01:09:46,000 --> 01:09:47,500
You would if you were
from New England.

995
01:09:47,500 --> 01:09:50,000
That guy was a very prominent
minister around here.

996
01:09:50,000 --> 01:09:52,000
Very important guy.

997
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:55,010
Then one day this book
comes out and tells
the world that he's gay

998
01:09:55,010 --> 01:09:58,010
and that he paid some woman
to have a baby for him,

999
01:09:58,010 --> 01:10:01,510
then the woman goes
and kills herself
and the baby.

1000
01:10:01,510 --> 01:10:02,510
Did you know him?

1001
01:10:02,510 --> 01:10:05,020
No. It was
way before our time.

1002
01:10:05,020 --> 01:10:07,020
Most of it's supposedly
not true anyway.

1003
01:10:07,020 --> 01:10:09,020
But don't tell
Mrs. Farthing that.

1004
01:10:09,020 --> 01:10:11,520
She makes everyone
read these books.

1005
01:10:11,520 --> 01:10:13,530
They're horrible.

1006
01:10:13,530 --> 01:10:16,030
But actually I like
his horror stuff.

1007
01:10:16,030 --> 01:10:19,530
I've never read any of it.
I used to think those books
looked kind of trashy.

1008
01:10:20,030 --> 01:10:23,040
Oh. You know,
I can lend them to you.

1009
01:10:23,040 --> 01:10:27,540
You should actually read them
because the first one was
written in your apartment.

1010
01:10:27,540 --> 01:10:29,040
Oh, okay. Thanks.

1011
01:10:29,040 --> 01:10:30,540
Sure.

1012
01:10:30,540 --> 01:10:32,540
[Mrs. Farthing]
Stacy!

1013
01:10:32,540 --> 01:10:35,050
See you later. Bye.

1014
01:11:03,710 --> 01:11:05,210
Aha.

1015
01:11:15,720 --> 01:11:19,230
Good afternoon, milady.
You're looking radiant today.

1016
01:11:19,220 --> 01:11:21,730
Thank you, Ted.
How are you?

1017
01:11:21,730 --> 01:11:25,230
Still plugging along.
Haven't seen you out
basking in the sun lately.

1018
01:11:25,230 --> 01:11:28,730
Oh, I have a new job.
It keeps me indoors a lot.

1019
01:11:28,730 --> 01:11:30,240
I'm doing research
on the Internet.

1020
01:11:30,740 --> 01:11:32,240
The Internet?
Of course.

1021
01:11:32,740 --> 01:11:34,240
Hey.

1022
01:11:35,740 --> 01:11:37,740
You want a cactus?

1023
01:11:37,740 --> 01:11:39,750
- What?
- It's a cactus.

1024
01:11:39,750 --> 01:11:41,750
They grow in the desert.
They don't take much water.

1025
01:11:41,750 --> 01:11:44,250
This one's been
in my back pocket
for I don't know how long.

1026
01:11:44,250 --> 01:11:45,750
You want it?

1027
01:11:46,250 --> 01:11:48,250
I don't think so.

1028
01:11:48,250 --> 01:11:49,760
I'm with you.

1029
01:11:49,760 --> 01:11:52,260
I can't seem to
stay away from plants.

1030
01:11:52,260 --> 01:11:54,760
Somebody
drops in for a visit,
they give me plant.

1031
01:11:54,760 --> 01:11:58,260
My nephew and his wife drive
all the way across country
from Amarillo.

1032
01:11:58,260 --> 01:12:00,270
They smuggle me a plant.

1033
01:12:00,270 --> 01:12:02,270
Comes my birthday,
all I ever get is plants.

1034
01:12:02,270 --> 01:12:03,770
Really?

1035
01:12:03,770 --> 01:12:06,270
I'm learning
to hate them.

1036
01:12:06,270 --> 01:12:08,270
Trees, yes,
but houseplants,

1037
01:12:08,270 --> 01:12:11,280
they shrivel up,
they get bugs and
spiders on them.

1038
01:12:11,280 --> 01:12:12,780
Who'd want them things
in their house?

1039
01:12:12,780 --> 01:12:16,280
And plus, our apartments
don't get very much sunlight.

1040
01:12:16,280 --> 01:12:17,780
You know, you're right.

1041
01:12:17,780 --> 01:12:21,290
Maybe that's why
mine are all dying.

1042
01:12:21,290 --> 01:12:22,790
What's that you're reading,
Ms. Kathryn?

1043
01:12:22,790 --> 01:12:24,790
Oh, uh, Peter Warren.

1044
01:12:24,790 --> 01:12:25,790
Oh.

1045
01:12:25,790 --> 01:12:27,790
That rattlesnake.

1046
01:12:27,790 --> 01:12:29,800
Not a good neighbor?

1047
01:12:30,300 --> 01:12:33,300
Good enough neighbor.
Just a bad man.

1048
01:12:33,300 --> 01:12:35,300
Really? How so?

1049
01:12:35,300 --> 01:12:37,300
I introduced him
to a friend of mine.

1050
01:12:37,300 --> 01:12:39,810
- Didn't end so good.
- Did something happen?

1051
01:12:40,310 --> 01:12:42,810
Well, it seemed like Warren
wanted to make it big

1052
01:12:42,810 --> 01:12:46,310
by exposing folk''
dirty laundry.

1053
01:12:46,310 --> 01:12:47,810
[sighs]

1054
01:12:47,810 --> 01:12:50,320
My friend worked
for this minister.

1055
01:12:50,320 --> 01:12:52,820
I suppose Mrs. Farthing
has forced that book
on you by now.

1056
01:12:52,820 --> 01:12:53,820
She has.

1057
01:12:54,320 --> 01:12:58,320
My friend Kurt looked after
the church grounds.

1058
01:12:58,320 --> 01:13:00,330
It paid chicken feed.

1059
01:13:00,330 --> 01:13:02,830
Time come when he needed
some cash real bad,

1060
01:13:03,330 --> 01:13:07,330
so he let himself
sell Warren
one hell of a story.

1061
01:13:07,330 --> 01:13:09,840
Anonymously,
of course.

1062
01:13:09,840 --> 01:13:12,340
There were things
going on at that rectory.

1063
01:13:12,340 --> 01:13:13,840
Nothing criminal.

1064
01:13:13,840 --> 01:13:17,340
Just stuff ordinary folks
might not expect
of a minister.

1065
01:13:17,340 --> 01:13:20,850
I read all about it,
but I didn't quite
understand it.

1066
01:13:20,850 --> 01:13:24,350
The reverend was gay,
but he paid some woman
to have his baby?

1067
01:13:24,350 --> 01:13:26,350
It didn't make
a whole lot of sense to me.

1068
01:13:26,350 --> 01:13:27,850
Warren exaggerated some.

1069
01:13:28,350 --> 01:13:31,360
Doesn't matter if
it was true or not.
It ruined the reverend.

1070
01:13:31,360 --> 01:13:32,860
Kurt never
forgave himself.

1071
01:13:32,860 --> 01:13:35,360
That's terrible.

1072
01:13:35,360 --> 01:13:37,360
That book did in
a lot of people.

1073
01:13:37,360 --> 01:13:40,370
Guilt can be
a real killer.

1074
01:13:40,870 --> 01:13:41,870
Yeah.

1075
01:13:42,370 --> 01:13:44,870
Say, Ms. Kathryn,
now that you're single,

1076
01:13:44,870 --> 01:13:47,370
maybe the two of us
could get together
for dinner and a drink

1077
01:13:47,370 --> 01:13:49,370
and some good talk.

1078
01:13:49,370 --> 01:13:51,380
Uh...

1079
01:13:51,380 --> 01:13:53,880
I think it's probably
a little too soon for me
to start dating again, Ted,

1080
01:13:54,380 --> 01:13:55,880
but thank you.

1081
01:13:55,880 --> 01:13:56,880
You're very sweet.

1082
01:13:56,880 --> 01:13:59,390
Well, you can't blame
an old fool for trying.

1083
01:13:59,380 --> 01:14:02,890
I'm going to check my mail,
then I'm off to the races.

1084
01:14:03,390 --> 01:14:04,890
- Good night.
- Good night.

1085
01:14:19,910 --> 01:14:22,410
[water running]

1086
01:15:11,960 --> 01:15:12,960
[Kathryn screams]

1087
01:15:17,960 --> 01:15:20,470
[screaming]

1088
01:15:25,970 --> 01:15:27,970
Oh, my God!
What's wrong, Kathryn?

1089
01:15:27,970 --> 01:15:30,980
Th-There's... m-m-man
in the show--

1090
01:15:30,980 --> 01:15:34,980
- Is it your boyfriend?
- No! Old man! Old man!

1091
01:15:34,980 --> 01:15:36,980
Are you all right?
Are you hurt?

1092
01:15:36,980 --> 01:15:39,490
[stammering]

1093
01:15:39,480 --> 01:15:41,490
Hello? Hello?

1094
01:15:41,490 --> 01:15:44,490
[gasping]

1095
01:15:44,490 --> 01:15:46,490
There's nobody
in there.

1096
01:15:46,490 --> 01:15:48,490
There's no one
in there. It's okay.

1097
01:15:48,990 --> 01:15:50,500
No! In the shower!

1098
01:15:50,500 --> 01:15:52,500
I didn't see anyone
in there. It's okay.

1099
01:15:52,500 --> 01:15:54,500
Just relax. Calm down.

1100
01:15:54,500 --> 01:15:58,500
Let's go to
Mrs. Farthing's place,
and we'll just relax.

1101
01:15:59,000 --> 01:16:02,010
- No one's in there?
- Nobody's in there.

1102
01:16:02,010 --> 01:16:04,010
Come on.
It's freezing.

1103
01:16:04,010 --> 01:16:06,510
[whimpering]

1104
01:16:06,510 --> 01:16:09,010
It's okay.

1105
01:16:09,010 --> 01:16:10,520
You're still
not well.

1106
01:16:10,520 --> 01:16:13,520
- It's okay.
- No, I'm all right.

1107
01:16:17,020 --> 01:16:20,030
Oh, God.
[whimpering]

1108
01:16:20,030 --> 01:16:22,030
I swear.
Nobody's in there.

1109
01:16:25,030 --> 01:16:27,030
Let's lie down
on the bed.

1110
01:16:29,530 --> 01:16:30,540
It's okay.

1111
01:16:42,550 --> 01:16:44,050
[tapping]

1112
01:16:50,060 --> 01:16:51,060
How you doing?

1113
01:16:51,560 --> 01:16:54,060
- Fine. Yourself?
- Not too bad.

1114
01:16:54,060 --> 01:16:57,060
I just hope the next time
you decide to go streaking,
you'll invite me.

1115
01:16:57,560 --> 01:16:59,060
[laughs]

1116
01:16:59,060 --> 01:17:01,570
How about a drink
with an old man?

1117
01:17:01,570 --> 01:17:03,570
I promise to be
a perfect gentleman,

1118
01:17:03,570 --> 01:17:06,570
and I won't
offer you a plant.

1119
01:17:06,570 --> 01:17:08,070
Um...

1120
01:17:08,070 --> 01:17:10,580
I'd love one.
A drink, not a plant.

1121
01:17:11,080 --> 01:17:14,580
- My place or yours?
- Yours. Definitely yours.

1122
01:17:19,580 --> 01:17:22,090
So, no union card,
no work.

1123
01:17:22,090 --> 01:17:26,090
That's mainly why
I retired from the rodeo.

1124
01:17:26,090 --> 01:17:27,590
Do you miss it?

1125
01:17:27,590 --> 01:17:30,600
I miss the crowds,
the cheering.

1126
01:17:30,600 --> 01:17:34,600
I miss the pretty ladies
who used to come up after,
looking to get acquainted.

1127
01:17:35,100 --> 01:17:38,100
But the ground got too hard,
my head got bonked
one too many times.

1128
01:17:38,100 --> 01:17:43,110
So I went roaming
God knows where.
I ended up here.

1129
01:17:43,110 --> 01:17:46,110
What brought you to Maine?

1130
01:17:46,110 --> 01:17:48,610
I come for the waters.

1131
01:17:49,110 --> 01:17:51,620
Time does go by,
but look at me.

1132
01:17:51,620 --> 01:17:54,620
I'm 76 years old,
I'm sitting here drinking
with a beautiful woman

1133
01:17:54,620 --> 01:17:56,120
young enough to be
my granddaughter.

1134
01:17:56,120 --> 01:17:58,620
Now, you promised
to be a gentleman.

1135
01:17:59,120 --> 01:18:01,130
Don't mind me,
Miss Kathryn.

1136
01:18:01,630 --> 01:18:04,130
I'm just a harmless
dirty old man.

1137
01:18:04,630 --> 01:18:07,130
Though you're the first lady
to come in this place since--

1138
01:18:07,130 --> 01:18:11,640
well, since the last time
Mrs. Farthing forced
spring-cleaning on me.

1139
01:18:11,640 --> 01:18:14,140
I had some
good times though.

1140
01:18:14,140 --> 01:18:15,140
Hold on a second.

1141
01:18:16,640 --> 01:18:19,640
You know, after you
got me talking about
my old friend Kurt,

1142
01:18:19,640 --> 01:18:21,650
I dug out these photos.

1143
01:18:22,150 --> 01:18:24,650
Sentimental, you know.

1144
01:18:24,650 --> 01:18:28,650
Oh, now, I know
I just saw one of him
in here somewhere.

1145
01:18:28,650 --> 01:18:31,160
- Is Kurt still alive?
- No.

1146
01:18:31,160 --> 01:18:35,160
He drank himself
to death.

1147
01:18:35,160 --> 01:18:37,160
That thing
with the minister.

1148
01:18:37,160 --> 01:18:39,160
That's terrible.

1149
01:18:39,160 --> 01:18:43,170
After Reverend Martin
hanged himself,
Kurt lost it.

1150
01:18:43,170 --> 01:18:48,170
I suppose I should feel
sort of responsible too,
but what's done is done.

1151
01:18:48,670 --> 01:18:52,180
- It's not your fault.
- That's what I told Kurt.

1152
01:18:52,180 --> 01:18:56,680
Kurt come here a day or two
before the book came out
and begged Warren to stop it.

1153
01:18:56,680 --> 01:18:58,680
Warren said
it was too late.

1154
01:18:58,680 --> 01:19:00,690
Kurt tried,
but what could he do?

1155
01:19:00,690 --> 01:19:04,190
I told him to leave his guilt
in that room with Warren
and get on with his life.

1156
01:19:04,190 --> 01:19:06,690
And did Warren ever
say anything to you about it?

1157
01:19:06,690 --> 01:19:08,690
Same thing he always said:

1158
01:19:08,690 --> 01:19:11,200
"The truth must come out."

1159
01:19:11,200 --> 01:19:13,700
I always wondered why,
if he was so concerned
about the truth,

1160
01:19:13,700 --> 01:19:17,700
he didn't use his own name
on those exposés.

1161
01:19:17,700 --> 01:19:20,210
And whatever happened
to the woman--

1162
01:19:20,210 --> 01:19:22,710
the woman who was paid
to have the reverend's baby?

1163
01:19:22,710 --> 01:19:24,210
So she claimed.

1164
01:19:24,210 --> 01:19:25,710
So it wasn't even true?

1165
01:19:27,210 --> 01:19:30,720
Reverend Martin was
as gay as a wind chime.

1166
01:19:30,720 --> 01:19:33,220
Baby was probably
some biker's.

1167
01:19:33,220 --> 01:19:37,220
But that crazy lady was obsessed
with the reverend and wanted
to be part of his life,

1168
01:19:37,220 --> 01:19:39,220
even if it was only
in Warren's book.

1169
01:19:39,220 --> 01:19:43,230
She even threatened
to kill Kurt if he told
anybody it wasn't true.

1170
01:19:43,230 --> 01:19:45,230
But why did she
kill the baby?

1171
01:19:45,730 --> 01:19:47,730
Psychotic.

1172
01:19:47,730 --> 01:19:51,740
She wouldn't
let up on Kurt,
Warren or Martin.

1173
01:19:52,240 --> 01:19:56,240
If she hadn't killed herself,
she'd still be here
hounding somebody.

1174
01:19:57,740 --> 01:19:59,240
Oh, wait a minute.
There it is.

1175
01:19:59,240 --> 01:20:01,750
That's Kurt and me.

1176
01:20:01,750 --> 01:20:05,750
We went to the races with
a few other old fogies.

1177
01:20:05,750 --> 01:20:08,250
Even won a few bucks.

1178
01:20:08,250 --> 01:20:11,260
That was the last time
I saw him smile.

1179
01:20:18,760 --> 01:20:22,770
You know, Ms. Kathryn,
Mrs. Farthing never even
let out that room

1180
01:20:22,770 --> 01:20:24,770
till you came along.

1181
01:20:24,770 --> 01:20:28,770
I think you kind of
brighten the place up.

1182
01:20:28,770 --> 01:20:30,780
I have to go.

1183
01:20:30,780 --> 01:20:31,780
Already?

1184
01:20:32,280 --> 01:20:34,280
- Oh, Ms. Kathryn, I'm sorry.
- No.

1185
01:20:34,780 --> 01:20:38,280
- I promised to be a gentleman.
- You were. Thank you.

1186
01:20:38,280 --> 01:20:40,790
Thank you.
Good night.

1187
01:20:42,290 --> 01:20:43,290
Night.

1188
01:21:12,820 --> 01:21:14,320
[click]

1189
01:21:15,820 --> 01:21:18,820
- Hi. It's me.
- Rick.

1190
01:21:18,820 --> 01:21:20,330
I hope you're doing okay.

1191
01:21:20,330 --> 01:21:22,830
I just wanted to call
and see how you were doing.

1192
01:21:22,830 --> 01:21:23,830
[click]

1193
01:21:25,830 --> 01:21:27,830
[woman]
Leave.

1194
01:22:38,900 --> 01:22:40,910
[rings]

1195
01:22:46,910 --> 01:22:47,910
[beeps]

1196
01:22:48,410 --> 01:22:49,410
[woman]
Kathryn?

1197
01:22:49,910 --> 01:22:51,920
Oh, my God.

1198
01:22:51,920 --> 01:22:54,920
Kathryn?
It's me, Mom.

1199
01:22:54,920 --> 01:22:57,920
- Mom!
- [high-pitched tone]

1200
01:22:57,920 --> 01:22:59,420
[woman]
Keep your mouth shut!

1201
01:23:03,930 --> 01:23:04,930
[rings]

1202
01:23:04,930 --> 01:23:07,930
Kathryn, it's time to leave.

1203
01:23:09,430 --> 01:23:12,440
You will stay here
and keep your mouth shut!

1204
01:23:13,940 --> 01:23:15,940
[rings]

1205
01:23:15,940 --> 01:23:17,440
Kathryn?

1206
01:23:20,450 --> 01:23:22,450
Mom, I'm sorry.

1207
01:23:22,450 --> 01:23:25,450
There is nothing for you
to feel sorry about, dear.

1208
01:23:25,450 --> 01:23:27,950
This guilt isn't yours.

1209
01:23:27,950 --> 01:23:30,460
It's time for you
to leave it behind.

1210
01:23:30,460 --> 01:23:32,460
[rumbling]

1211
01:24:09,990 --> 01:24:12,000
Kathryn!

1212
01:24:12,000 --> 01:24:14,000
Kathryn!

1213
01:24:17,000 --> 01:24:18,500
Kathryn!

1214
01:24:20,000 --> 01:24:22,510
Stupid damn keys.

1215
01:24:24,510 --> 01:24:27,510
Never could get
these keys to work.

1216
01:24:27,510 --> 01:24:30,520
Kathryn, open the door!

1217
01:24:30,520 --> 01:24:32,520
Kathryn, go!

1218
01:24:35,020 --> 01:24:37,020
I love you.

1219
01:24:42,530 --> 01:24:44,030
I love you.

1220
01:24:47,820 --> 01:24:50,620
- [knocking]
- [Mrs. Farthing]
Kathryn, are you there?

1221
01:24:50,620 --> 01:24:52,620
Kathryn, answer me!

1222
01:25:31,610 --> 01:25:34,610
[Kathryn]
I can take one more question
before the signing begins.

1223
01:25:34,610 --> 01:25:36,110
- Yes?
- Ms. Bennett.

1224
01:25:36,110 --> 01:25:40,120
Your first book focused
on Peter Warren's
earlier career,

1225
01:25:40,620 --> 01:25:44,120
writing kiss-and-tell books
under the name of
"Monty Briggs."

1226
01:25:44,120 --> 01:25:47,130
Now you write about
Warren himself,

1227
01:25:47,130 --> 01:25:51,130
saying that the inspiration
for his best-selling
horror novels

1228
01:25:51,630 --> 01:25:54,130
comes from
his own delusions,

1229
01:25:54,130 --> 01:25:57,640
that he is plagued by
the guilt-ridden ghosts

1230
01:25:57,640 --> 01:26:00,640
of people whose trust
you claim he betrayed.

1231
01:26:01,140 --> 01:26:04,640
What do you say to
your critics who feel
that your current work

1232
01:26:04,640 --> 01:26:08,150
is just as exploitative as
the supermarket paperbacks

1233
01:26:08,650 --> 01:26:11,650
that you criticize Warren
for having written?

1234
01:26:13,150 --> 01:26:15,650
The truth must come out.

1235
